description.narrative:
The #Fair Trade# project in Nampula, Mozambique, aims to help farmers generate more income from their production of cashew nuts, peanuts and sesame. The project started in March 2015. It is implemented by AENA (the National Association of Rural ExtensionWorkers) and Oxfam and is funded by the ASN Bank, a bank based in the Netherlands.
In year one the project has started well, 60% of the targeted farmers are already organized in well-functioning associations. The groups produced peanuts and sesame for the next season. Jointly they are working on fair-trade certification before the first harvest of cashew nuts.
For year 2 , the main focus will b on training communities on certification standards and also bringing expertises from South Africa to help local associations to get the certificates

GOAL: To improve the livelihood (mainly food security and family income) of small scale farmers through creating an enabling environment for Fair Trade of sesame, cashew nuts and peanuts in 4 districts of the Nampula province in Mozambique.
STRATEGIC OBJECTIVE: To develop a robust platform composed of 2,000 individual and aggregated farmers in 4 districts of the Nampula province (Meconta, Monapo, Muecateand Murrupula).
Outcomes
1. Viable agribusiness cooperatives/associations effectively linked to a more fair value chain;
2. 2000 farmers increases their average productivity (kg per hectare) by at least 80%;
3. 2000 farmers increased their average profit income by US$ 200 per year;
